Body shape as shown in 
Figures 7A and C
, generally slender oval, sometimes asymmetric with straight right margin (
Figure 10J
). Mostly about 100×60 Mm in size. Buccal field medium–wide, about two-thirds of cell length. Macronucleus typically C-shaped (
Figures 7B, C
). No micronucleus detected. Ridges on dorsal side inconspicuous, along ciliary rows (
Figure 10I
), while on ventral side typically as seen in most other congeners (
Figure 10J
).

Up to now, over 80 nominal 

Euplotes

(s. l.) have been reported, and among them no species have been described possessing different-sized marginal cirri (
Kahl 1932
; 
Curds 1975
; 
Dragesco and Dragesco-Kernéis 1986
; 
Valbonesi and Luporini 1990
; 
Song and Wilbert 1997
). Hence the phenomenon found in 

E. dragescoi

is unique in that one marginal cirrus is extremely ‘‘reduced’’.
